Under the pale glow of the moon, a lone wolf named Arin moved through the snow‑dusted forest with a grace that made the night seem to part for him. His paws pressed soft prints into the earth, each step deliberate, each breath a small cloud drifting into the cold air. He paused at the edge of a clearing, ears pricked, listening to the distant crackle of ice shifting on the river. For a moment, he stood perfectly still, a silhouette carved from shadow and silver light. Then, with a quiet certainty, Arin lifted his head and continued forward, guided not by sight but by the ancient pull of instinct that had carried his kind across countless winters.